# Module Composition

Real-world infrastructure is built by composing multiple modules together. A production environment typically combines networking (VPC), compute (EKS, ECS, EC2), databases (RDS, ElastiCache), and security (IAM, security groups) modules into a cohesive stack.

## Composition Patterns

### 1. Flat Composition

The most common pattern. The root module calls multiple child modules at the same level:

```hcl
# Root module: environments/production/main.tf

module "vpc" {
  source = "./modules/vpc"
  cidr   = "10.0.0.0/16"
  azs    = ["us-east-1a", "us-east-1b", "us-east-1c"]
}

module "eks" {
  source     = "./modules/eks"
  vpc_id     = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.vpc.private_subnet_ids

  cluster_name    = "production"
  cluster_version = "1.29"
  node_groups = {
    default = {
      instance_types = ["m6i.xlarge"]
      min_size       = 3
      max_size       = 10
    }
  }
}

module "rds" {
  source     = "./modules/rds"
  vpc_id     = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.vpc.database_subnet_ids

  engine         = "postgres"
  engine_version = "15.4"
  instance_class = "db.r6g.xlarge"
  database_name  = "app"

  allowed_security_group_ids = [module.eks.node_security_group_id]
}
```

Flat composition is easy to understand and debug. Dependencies are explicit through output references.

### 2. Nested Modules

Modules calling other modules internally. Useful for building higher-level abstractions:

```hcl
# modules/platform/main.tf
# A "platform" module that internally composes VPC + EKS

module "vpc" {
  source = "../vpc"
  cidr   = var.vpc_cidr
  azs    = var.azs
}

module "eks" {
  source     = "../eks"
  vpc_id     = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.vpc.private_subnet_ids

  cluster_name    = var.cluster_name
  cluster_version = var.cluster_version
}

# Expose key outputs
output "cluster_endpoint" {
  value = module.eks.cluster_endpoint
}

output "vpc_id" {
  value = module.vpc.vpc_id
}
```

Nested modules reduce the root module's complexity but can hide important details. Use sparingly -- prefer flat composition unless there is a strong abstraction boundary.

### 3. Module Wrapper Pattern

A thin wrapper that configures an upstream module with organizational defaults:

```hcl
# modules/org-vpc/main.tf
# Wrapper around the community VPC module with org defaults

module "vpc" {
  source  = "terraform-aws-modules/vpc/aws"
  version = "~> 5.0"

  name = var.name
  cidr = var.cidr
  azs  = var.azs

  private_subnets  = var.private_subnets
  public_subnets   = var.public_subnets
  database_subnets = var.database_subnets

  # Organizational defaults
  enable_nat_gateway   = true
  single_nat_gateway   = var.environment != "production"
  enable_dns_hostnames = true
  enable_dns_support   = true

  tags = merge(var.tags, {
    ManagedBy   = "terraform"
    Environment = var.environment
    CostCenter  = var.cost_center
  })
}

# Pass through all outputs
output "vpc_id" {
  value = module.vpc.vpc_id
}

output "private_subnet_ids" {
  value = module.vpc.private_subnets
}
```

Wrappers enforce standards (tagging, naming, security) while leveraging community-maintained modules.

## Passing Data Between Modules

Modules communicate exclusively through outputs and variables. There is no shared state or global scope:

```hcl
# Module A exposes an output
output "vpc_id" {
  description = "The VPC ID"
  value       = aws_vpc.this.id
}

# Module B consumes it as a variable
variable "vpc_id" {
  description = "VPC ID to deploy into"
  type        = string
}

# Root module wires them together
module "a" {
  source = "./modules/a"
}

module "b" {
  source = "./modules/b"
  vpc_id = module.a.vpc_id  # output -> variable
}
```

This creates an implicit dependency: Terraform knows `module.b` depends on `module.a` because it references `module.a.vpc_id`. In rare cases where there is a dependency without a data reference, use explicit `depends_on`:

```hcl
module "app" {
  source = "./modules/app"

  depends_on = [module.iam_policies]
}
```

## Module-to-Module Contracts

Design clear interfaces between modules. A module's outputs are its API:

```hcl
# VPC module contract (outputs.tf)
# Any compute module can consume these outputs
output "vpc_id"              { value = aws_vpc.this.id }
output "private_subnet_ids"  { value = aws_subnet.private[*].id }
output "public_subnet_ids"   { value = aws_subnet.public[*].id }
output "database_subnet_ids" { value = aws_subnet.database[*].id }
output "vpc_cidr_block"      { value = aws_vpc.this.cidr_block }

# EKS module contract (variables.tf)
# Expects outputs from a VPC-like module
variable "vpc_id"     { type = string }
variable "subnet_ids" { type = list(string) }
```

Stable contracts allow modules to evolve independently. Adding new outputs is safe; removing or renaming outputs is a breaking change (major version bump).

## Real-World Composition: VPC + EKS + RDS

A complete production stack wiring three modules together:

```hcl
locals {
  environment = "production"
  region      = "us-east-1"
  azs         = ["us-east-1a", "us-east-1b", "us-east-1c"]
}

module "vpc" {
  source = "./modules/vpc"

  name = "prod"
  cidr = "10.0.0.0/16"
  azs  = local.azs

  private_subnets  = ["10.0.1.0/24", "10.0.2.0/24", "10.0.3.0/24"]
  public_subnets   = ["10.0.101.0/24", "10.0.102.0/24", "10.0.103.0/24"]
  database_subnets = ["10.0.201.0/24", "10.0.202.0/24", "10.0.203.0/24"]
}

module "eks" {
  source = "./modules/eks"

  cluster_name = "prod-cluster"
  vpc_id       = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids   = module.vpc.private_subnet_ids
}

module "rds" {
  source = "./modules/rds"

  identifier = "prod-db"
  vpc_id     = module.vpc.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = module.vpc.database_subnet_ids

  # Allow EKS nodes to connect
  allowed_security_group_ids = [module.eks.node_security_group_id]
}

# Wire database connection to EKS via SSM Parameter Store
resource "aws_ssm_parameter" "db_endpoint" {
  name  = "/prod/database/endpoint"
  type  = "SecureString"
  value = module.rds.endpoint
}
```

Dependency graph: `vpc` -> `eks` and `rds` (both depend on VPC outputs), `rds` -> `eks` (needs security group ID). Terraform resolves the graph automatically.

## Terragrunt for DRY Multi-Module Orchestration

Terragrunt is a thin wrapper around Terraform that reduces repetition across environments:

```hcl
# terragrunt.hcl (root)
remote_state {
  backend = "s3"
  generate = {
    path      = "backend.tf"
    if_exists = "overwrite_terragrunt"
  }
  config = {
    bucket         = "my-terraform-state"
    key            = "${path_relative_to_include()}/terraform.tfstate"
    region         = "us-east-1"
    dynamodb_table = "terraform-locks"
    encrypt        = true
  }
}

# environments/production/vpc/terragrunt.hcl
terraform {
  source = "../../../modules/vpc"
}

include "root" {
  path = find_in_parent_folders()
}

inputs = {
  name = "prod"
  cidr = "10.0.0.0/16"
}

# environments/production/eks/terragrunt.hcl
terraform {
  source = "../../../modules/eks"
}

include "root" {
  path = find_in_parent_folders()
}

dependency "vpc" {
  config_path = "../vpc"
}

inputs = {
  cluster_name = "prod"
  vpc_id       = dependency.vpc.outputs.vpc_id
  subnet_ids   = dependency.vpc.outputs.private_subnet_ids
}
```

Terragrunt provides: `dependency` blocks for cross-state references, `include` for DRY configuration, `run-all` for applying multiple modules in dependency order, and auto-generated backend configs.
